rofessor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (September 24, 1912)</ref>\n|-\n| October 9, 1913\n| [[Szeged]], [[Hungary]]\n| Johann Skultety, 14\n| 1 dead\n| \n| After he had been reprimanded by his teacher, Prof. Horvarth, for missing classes, Johann Skultety, a gymnasium student in Szeged, barged into his classroom and fired with a revolver at the teacher, missing him. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the heart.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19131010&seite=3&zoom=2 Ein Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf seinen Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (October 10, 1913)</ref>\n|-\n| April 12, 1919\n| [[Ogden City, Utah]], United States\n| \n| \n|1 injured\n|During a high school assembly, six boys shot off their guns, with permission, thinking they were loaded with blanks. Teacher Miss Verna Davidson was shot in the foot.<ref>''The Ogden Standard,'' April 26, 1919</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1920s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n|February 14, 1920\n|[[Durant, Oklahoma]], United States\n|\n| \n|1 injured\n|At Durant Normal School, teacher Albert McFarland was shot and seriously wounded by one of his pupils.<ref>''The Daily Ardmoreite'' (Ardmore, Okla.), February 15, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 4, 1920\n|[[Cincinnati, Ohio]], United States\n| Lawrence Angel, 14\n| \n| 1 injured\n|A student, 14-year-old Lawrence Angel, shot his teacher Beatrice Conner through the arm for sending him to the principal's office.<ref>''The Bismarck Tribune'' (Bismarck, N.D.), March 04, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|March 12, 1920\n|[[Newberry, South Carolina]], United States\n|William Scott\n| \n|1 injured\n|William Scott, a student at Helena Colored School, shot Henry Gray, another student.<ref>''The Herald and News''', (Newberry S.C.), March 12, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|May 1, 1920\n|[[Summerville, Georgia]], United States\n|Alexander Potter, 15\n| \n|\n|At the High School, a student, 15-year-old Alexander Potter, fired six shots at his teacher, Prof. Ransom, but missed, upset after a severe thrashing. Potter was sentenced to 6 years at a reform school.<ref>The Watchman and Southron.(Sumter, S.C.), May 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n|November 4, 1920\n|[[Middlesboro, Kentucky]], United States\n| Adolphus Oaks\n| 1 dead\n|\n|Prof. Barnes of Middlesboro High School was fatally shot by Adolphus Oaks, for whipping his sister the week before. Oaks went to jail.<ref>''The Ogden Standard-Examiner'' (Ogden, Utah), November 05, 1920</ref>\n|-\n| May 6, 1925\n| [[Wilno]], Poland\n| Two to three students\n| 5+ dead\n| ~10 injured\n| [[Wilno school massacre]]. A massacre occurred at [[Joachim Lelewel]] High School in [[Wilno]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. At about 11 a.m., during the final exams, at least two eighth-grade students attacked the board of examiners with revolvers and hand grenades, killing at least one teacher, several students and themselves. An investigation revealed that the students had established a Communist youth organisation to counter the principal's strict management of the school. The members of this organisation had met the day before the exams in a tavern, to discuss the actions. <ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nfp&datum=19250507&seite=1&zoom=2 Revolversch\u00fcsse und Bombenw\u00fcrfe gegen Lehrer], ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A16FF3B5B12738DDDAE0894DD405B858EF1D3 Bomb Kills Three Boy Raiders Who Shoot Up Vilna School], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref>\n|-\n| May 18, 1927\n| [[Bath, Michigan]], United States\n| [[Andrew Kehoe]], 55\n| 45\n| 58\n| [[Bath School disaster]]. School board member [[Andrew Kehoe]] set up a series of explosions in the [[Bath Consolidated School]].  Before blowing up the school, Kehoe murdered his wife and set fire to his farmhouse.  After the bombings, Kehoe detonated his shrapnel-filled vehicle outside the school, committing suicide and wounding others. The bombings constitutes the deadliest act of mass murder in any type of school setting in U.S. history.\n|}\n\n===1930s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 5, 1931\n| [[Pristina]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n|\n|\n| 1 injured\n| A student named Ismailovic shot and stabbed his teacher several times at a gymnasium in Pristina after he had been expelled due to low grades. Ismailovic was later arrested at a cemetery when he tried to hang himself.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19310306&seite=5&zoom=2 Die Rache eines durchgefallenen Gymnasiasten], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (March 6, 1931)</ref>\n|-\n| September 14, 1934\n| [[Gill, Massachusetts]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Headmaster Elliott Speer was murdered by a shotgun blast through the window of his study at [[Northfield Mount Hermon School]]. The crime was never solved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,848774,00.html |title=Education: Berkshire Mystery |publisher=Time.com |date=1937-06-07 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 24, 1937\n| [[Toledo, Ohio]], United States\n| Robert Snyder, 12\n|\n| 2 injured\n| 12-year-old Robert Snyder shot and wounded his principal, June Mapes, in her office at Arlington public school when she declined his request to call a classmate. He later shot and wounded himself but survived.<ref>[https