l=https://www.apr.org/post/mental-evaluation-sought-school-traffic-shooting-suspect|title=Mental evaluation sought for school traffic shooting suspect|first=Associated|last=Press|website=www.apr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/08/26/isaiah-johnson-charged-escape-after-blount-elementary-shooting/2121409001/|title=Father charged in Blount Elementary shooting re-arrested after escaping treatment facility|first=Melissa|last=Brown|website=The Montgomery Advertiser}}</ref>\n|-\n| August 30, 2019\n| Mobile, Alabama\n| Deangelo Dejuan Parnell, 17\n| 0\n| 10 injured\n| Parnell shot 9 people during a confrontation at a stadium where a high school football game was being played. A tenth person suffered a stroke.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/31/us/mobile-alabama-football-shooting.html|title=At Least 10 Shot at Alabama High School Football Game, Police Say|first=Derrick Bryson|last=Taylor|date=August 31, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| October 1, 2019\n| [[Kuopio]], Finland\n| Joel Marin, 25\n| 1 dead\n| 10 injured\n| [[Kuopio school stabbing]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019 \n| Santa Clarita, California\n| Nathaniel Berhow, 16\n| 3 dead\n| 3 injured \n| [[Saugus High School shooting]]\n|-\n| November 14, 2019\n| [[Blagoveshchensk]], Russia\n| Daniil Zasorin, 19\n| 2 dead\n| 3 injured\n| After being told to leave the classroom twice, Zasorin returned with a pump-action shotgun and opened fire in the room, shooting victims at their desks. He committed suicide after being wounded in exchange of gunfire with police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/russia-college-shooting-daniil-zasorin-attack-death-toll-latest-today-a9202526.html|title=Gunman opens fire in deadly Russian college attack after posting bizarre message online|date=14 November 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[School bullying]]\n*[[School shooting]]\n*[[List of school-related attacks]]\n*[[List of school shootings in the United States]]\n*[[List of attacks related to primary schools]]\n*[[List of attacks related to post-secondary schools]]\n*[[List of rampage killers: School massacres]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|refs=\n<ref name=note_a>Including death or injury of attacker(s), when applicable.</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181140/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence00-01.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2000\u20132001], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181216/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence02-03.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2002\u20132003], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181239/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence04-05.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2004\u20132005], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181347/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence06-07.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2006\u20132007], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181441/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence07-08.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2007\u20132008], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181632/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence08-09.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2008\u20132009], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722181945/http://www.schoolsecurity.org/trends/school_violence09-10.html School-Related Deaths, School Shootings, & School Violence Incidents: 2009\u20132010], ''National School Safety and Security Services''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:School-Related Attacks}}\n[[Category:Attacks on schools|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of schools|*]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Secondary education-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of school-related attacks|secondary]]\n", "name_user": "BorderRegions", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1980s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_attacks_related_to_secondary_schools"}
{"title_page": "Roy Skinner", "text_new": "'''Roy Gene Skinner''' (April 17, 1930 &ndash; October 25, 2010) was an American [[basketball]] coach who was best known for his time as head coach of [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball]]. Skinner helped break the racial barrier by recruiting the first [[African American]] athlete to play varsity ball for a team in the [[Southeastern Conference]].  He has the second-most wins in program history, behind [[Kevin Stallings]].\n\n==Life and career==\nSkinner was born in 1930 in [[Paducah, Kentucky]]. He played basketball as a [[point guard]] in high school, at [[Paducah Junior College]], and at [[Presbyterian College]], where he earned his undergraduate degree in 1952. His first basketball coaching job was in 1955 at his alma mater Paducah Junior College in 1955 (now part of [[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]]).<ref>[http://vucommodores.cstv.com/genrel/022807aaa.html Legendary Coach Roy Skinner], accessed October 31, 2010</ref>\n\nHe was hired by head coach [[Bob Polk]] at Vanderbilt as an assistant coach two years later after Skinner led his Paducah team to a win against Vanderbilt's freshman squad.<ref name=TennesseeanObit/> He spent the 1958-59 season as the acting head coach in Polk's absence, and led the team to an overall record of 14-10.<ref name=NYTObit>Slotnick, Daniel E. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/31/sports/ncaabasketball/31skinner.html \"Roy Skinner, Who Recruited First Black Basketball Player in SEC, Dies at 80\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 30, 2010. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref>\n\nSkinner succeeded Polk as head coach in the 1960-61 season. With the support of [[Vanderbilt University]] chancellor [[G. Alexander Heard]], he pursued the recruitment of African American players for the basketball team. The first player to make the team was [[Perry Wallace]], a local schoolboy star at Nashville's Pearl High School, who enrolled at Vanderbilt in 1966 and first started playing for the team in 1967, becoming the Southeastern Conference's first African American varsity player. Skinner faced opposition from alumni who were opposed to integrating the team;\nSkinner was primarily looking at recruiting Wallace as someone who would be \"a great player, and also a great student, a valedictorian\" and that the fact that he was making history was a secondary aspect of the choice.<ref name=NYTObit/> Wallace recalled in a 2009 interview that Skinner practically lived at his house from the time he started trying to recruit him while he was a high school junior.<ref>English, Antonya. [http://www.tampabay.com/sports/basketball/college/article970327.ece \"Former Vanderbilt star Perry Wallace learned to overcome hatred as Southeastern Conference's first black basketball player\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100710033658/http://www.tampabay.com/sports/basketball/college/article970327.ece |date=2010-07-10 }}, ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'', January 25, 2009. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref>\n\nSkinner led the team to the Elite Eight in the [[1965 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] behind a 24&ndash;4 record that season, losing to the [[University of Michigan]] by two points.<ref name=TennesseeanObit/> Skinner was chosen as coach of the year in the SEC in 1974 by the [[Associated Press]] after leading the team to a 23&ndash;3 season record, with Skinner receiving seven votes from the 10-member board that selected the winner.<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>via [[Associated Press]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LPtEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=J1gDAAAAIBAJ&dq=roy%20skinner%20vanderbilt&pg=4042%2C3999386 \"Vanderbilt Coach Top SEC Skinner\"], ''[[Evening Independent]]'', March 13, 1974. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> Saying that \"I don't want to get old being basketball coach\", Skinner announced in March 1976 that he would be stepping down as head coach after 16 years and turning the reins over to assistant head coach [[Wayne Dobbs]].<ref>Staff. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dBEQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0IwDAAAAIBAJ&dq=roy%20skinner%20vanderbilt&pg=4861%2C1354566 \"Vanderbilt's Roy Skinner retires after 16 years\"], ''[[Boca Raton News]]'', March 10, 1976. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> Skinner led the Commodores to a 278-135 record during his tenure, the most in school history until [[Kevin Stallings]] passed him during the 2013-14 season.  He was named SEC coach of the year in 1965, 1967, 1974 and 1976.<ref>Mullen, Bryan. [http://www.tennessean.com/article/20101031/SPORTS0602/10310367/2082/sports \"Vanderbilt Commodores pay tribute to Roy Skinner: Vanderbilt Commodores fans, players remember former coach\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]'', October 31, 2010. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> In 2009, Skinner was inducted into the Vanderbilt Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name=TennesseeanObit>Lockridge, Jeff. [http://www.tennessean.com/article/20101026/SPORTS0602/10260346/2082/SPORTS \"Vanderbilt Commodores legend Roy Skinner dies: Skinner was Vanderbilt Commodores' winningest basketball coach\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]'', October 26, 2010. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSkinner died in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] at the age of 80 on October 25, 2010, due to [[respiratory failure]]. He was survived by his third wife, Nathleene, as well as by two daughters, three sons and eight grandchildren, all from his first marriage.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skinner, Roy}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Deaths from respiratory failure]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Junior college men's basketball coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Junior college men's basketball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Presbyterian Blue Hose men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paducah, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n", "text_old": "'''Roy Gene Skinner''' (April 17, 1930 &ndash; October 25, 2010) was an American [[basketball]] coach who was best known for his time as head coach of [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball]]. Skinner helped break the racial barrier by recruiting the first [[African American]] athlete to play varsity ball for a team in the [[Southeastern Conference]].  He has the second-most wins in program history, behind [[Kevin Stallings]].\n\n==Life and career==\nSkinner was born in 1930 in [[Paducah, Kentucky]]. He played basketball as a [[point guard]] in high school, at [[Paducah Junior College]], and at [[Presbyterian College]], where he earned his undergraduate degree in 1952. His first basketball coaching job was in 1955 at his alma mater Paducah Junior College in 1955 (now part of [[West Kentucky Community and Technical College]]).<ref>[http://vucommodores.cstv.com/genrel/022807aaa.html Legendary Coach Roy Skinner], accessed October 31, 2010</ref>\n\nHe was hired by head coach [[Bob Polk]] at Vanderbilt as an assistant coach two years later after Skinner led his Paducah team to a win against Vanderbilt's freshman squad.<ref name=TennesseeanObit/> He spent the 1958-59 season as the acting head coach in Polk's absence, and led the team to an overall record of 14-10.<ref name=NYTObit>Slotnick, Daniel E. [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/31/sports/ncaabasketball/31skinner.html \"Roy Skinner, Who Recruited First Black Basketball Player in SEC, Dies at 80\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 30, 2010. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref>\n\nSkinner succeeded Polk as head coach in the 1960-61 season. With the support of [[Vanderbilt University]] chancellor [[G. Alexander Heard]], he pursued the recruitment of African American players for the basketball team. The first player to make the team was [[Perry Wallace]], a local schoolboy star at Nashville's Pearl High School, who enrolled at Vanderbilt in 1966 and first started playing for the team in 1967, becoming the Southeastern Conference's first African American varsity player. Skinner faced opposition from alumni who were opposed to integrating the team;\nSkinner was primarily looking at recruiting Wallace as someone who would be \"a great player, and also a great student, a valedictorian\" and that the fact that he was making history was a secondary aspect of the choice.<ref name=NYTObit/> Wallace recalled in a 2009 interview that Skinner practically lived at his house from the time he started trying to recruit him while he was a high school junior.<ref>English, Antonya. [http://www.tampabay.com/sports/basketball/college/article970327.ece \"Former Vanderbilt star Perry Wallace learned to overcome hatred as Southeastern Conference's first black basketball player\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100710033658/http://www.tampabay.com/sports/basketball/college/article970327.ece |date=2010-07-10 }}, ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'', January 25, 2009. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref>\n\nSkinner led the team to the Elite Eight in the [[1965 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] behind a 24&ndash;4 record that season, losing to the [[University of Michigan]] by two points.<ref name=TennesseeanObit/> Skinner was chosen as coach of the year in the SEC in 1974 by the [[Associated Press]] after leading the team to a 23&ndash;3 season record, with Skinner receiving seven votes from the 10-member board that selected the winner.<ref name=NYTObit/><ref>via [[Associated Press]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=LPtEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=J1gDAAAAIBAJ&dq=roy%20skinner%20vanderbilt&pg=4042%2C3999386 \"Vanderbilt Coach Top SEC Skinner\"], ''[[Evening Independent]]'', March 13, 1974. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> Saying that \"I don't want to get old being basketball coach\", Skinner announced in March 1976 that he would be stepping down as head coach after 16 years and turning the reins over to assistant head coach [[Wayne Dobbs]].<ref>Staff. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dBEQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0IwDAAAAIBAJ&dq=roy%20skinner%20vanderbilt&pg=4861%2C1354566 \"Vanderbilt's Roy Skinner retires after 16 years\"], ''[[Boca Raton News]]'', March 10, 1976. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> Skinner led the Commodores to a 278-135 record during his tenure, the most in school history until [[Kevin Stallings]] passed him during the 2013-14 season.  He was named SEC coach of the year in 1965, 1967, 1974 and 1976.<ref>Mullen, Bryan. [http://www.tennessean.com/article/20101031/SPORTS0602/10310367/2082/sports \"Vanderbilt Commodores pay tribute to Roy Skinner: Vanderbilt Commodores fans, players remember former coach\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]'', October 31, 2010. Accessed October 31, 2010.</ref> In 2009, Skinner was inducted into the Vanderbilt Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name=TennesseeanObit>Lockridge, Jeff. [http://www.tennessean.com/article/20101026/SPORTS0602/10260346/2082/SPORTS \"Vanderbilt Commodores legend Roy Skinner dies: Skinner was Vanderbilt Commodores' winningest basketball coach\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]'', October 26, 2010. Accessed october 31, 2010.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nSkinner died in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] at the age of 80 on October 25, 2010, due to [[respiratory failure]]. He was survived by his third wife, Nathleene, as well as by two daughters, three sons and eight grandchildren, all from his first marriage.<ref name=NYTObit/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skinner, Roy}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Basketball 